\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 parties of winter-travelers per unit area (e.g.
 square kilometer or square mile).
 If there are few-enough parties that they only ever get caught in their
 own avalanches, one expects the avalanche-accident rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\text{avalanche}}$
\end_inset

, to be proportional to the total area of the start zones (
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\text{startzones}}$
\end_inset

) and the party density:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{\text{avalanche}}\propto A_{\text{startzones}}n\label{eq:Single party avalanche rate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The implications are straightforward: More parties, proportionally more
 accidents.
 More/larger start zones, proportionally more accidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What if there are enough parties around that there's a chance that one group
 could trigger a slide that hits another group?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two factors that are important:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When there are more parties in an area, they will trigger more avalanches
 (probability 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\text{startzones}}n$
\end_inset

), just as before.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the average avalanche that day sweeps through a total area 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\text{avalanche}}$
\end_inset

, the rate at which other parties might be struck by that avalanche is then
 approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\text{avalanche}}n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, the rate of inter-party avalanche accidents, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\text{interparty}}$
\end_inset

, ought to scale like
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{\text{interparty}}\propto A_{\text{startzones}}A_{\text{avalanche}}n^{2}.\label{eq:Quadratic Scaling}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\series bold
The rate of multi-party accidents should scale like the skier-density 
\emph on
squared
\series default
\emph default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

).
 This is this paper's key observation.
 Everything that follows is only to argue that the time is now to be concerned
 about inter-party accidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why is 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 important? Let's look at the probability that our parties will be involved
 in an accident of either kind by summing the probabilities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{\text{accident}}=R_{\text{avalanche}}+R_{\text{interparty}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{\text{accident}}\propto A_{\text{start-zones}}(n+A_{\text{avalanche}}n^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or, suggestively,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{\text{accident}}\propto A_{\text{start-zones}}n(1+A_{\text{avalanche}}n)\label{eq:Combined Single and multi-party accident rate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the skier density, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, is small, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is smaller still, just as 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.1)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 0.01.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is larger than 1, though, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 dominates the problem, just as 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 100.
 What, then, sets the scale of "1" ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Combined Single and multi-party accident rate"

\end_inset

 holds the answer: it is the size of the day's typical avalanche that matters.
 Once 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{avalanche}n>1$
\end_inset

, inter-party incidents will dominate.
 This is a common-sense idea – once there is roughly one party per avalanche-are
a, any triggered avalanche is likely to hit another party.
 This notion makes intuitive sense – in-bounds avalanches at ski areas are
 scary in part because the skier density is so high.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relationship of multi-party accident rate to avalanche size
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Quadratic Scaling"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Combined Single and multi-party accident rate"

\end_inset

 suggest an important corollary: If the size or likelihood of a day's avalanches
 is greater, we should expect the rate at which multi-party accidents occur
 to be greater.
 If slides are more likely/larger, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\text{startzones}}$
\end_inset

 will tend to increase, and if slides are larger, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\text{avalanche}}$
\end_inset

 is surely larger.
 As backcountry travelers, larger and more-likely slides will force wary
 travelers to consider larger areas (further uphill) and more places (increased
 number of potential start zones) in the context of inter-party accidents.
\end_layout

