\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Mitigation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Mitigation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is unlikely, and perhaps undesireable, that the number of backcountry
 travelers be reduced.
 Therefore, we must find ways to limit the likelihood of inter-party accidents.
 The following are a few strategies that may mitigate the risk.
 There are certainly more – these are suggested to organize and catalyze
 discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Density reduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The root of inter-party accidents is not the 
\emph on
number
\emph default
 of backcountry travelers, but their 
\emph on
density
\emph default
.
 Backcountry travelers use a tiny fraction of North American alpine terrain,
 perhaps primarily due to access constraints.
 Following the Kendall Peak accident
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "KendallDecember19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the author has sharply curtailed trips into densely-skied terrain, choosing
 lesser-known destinations, difficult access, or lower-quality snow in order
 to decrease overhead risk from other parties.
 While this strategy has limits, there are still lonely places with great
 skiing to be found on the map.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As advocacy organizations work to expand wintertime access, it may be reasonable
 to add safety to the reasons for improved access.
 Inferring our from introductory analysis, it is natural to encourage party
 densities below one per characteristic-avalanche-size (XXXRC < 0.1-1 parties/acr
e?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Travel practices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If density cannot be wholly avoided, then we must find ways to limit our
 susceptibility to other parties and the risks we may pose to others.
 We cannot control others' choices, but we can control our own.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Defensive routefinding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like defensive driving, defensive routefinding consists of making choices
 that mitigate the risks that others may pose.
 Careful selection of routes through terrain, and, to a lesser extent, times
 to pass through terrain, can strongly limit the chance that another party's
 avalanche might hit us.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Examples: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Many ridgelines are not susceptible to slides from above – travelling upon
 such a ridgeline inherently provides substantial protection from any inter-part
y accident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some routes pass through areas of unavoidable avalanche hazard – there are
 plenty of famous examples: The Mousetrap
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MousetrapAsulkanGuide"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 at Roger's Pass, Source Lake Basin at Snoqualmie Pass.
 Avoiding those areas during times that 
\emph on
human-triggered
\emph default
 slides are likely, rather than only when natural slides are likely, will
 limit the risk of an inter-party accident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The particular examples of the Hawkins Mountain (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Hawkins"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and Turbo Hillclimb (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Turbo"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) accidents make clear the danger of extended loitering in inter-party-avalanche
 terrain.
 When assessing safe spots, the likelihood of human triggers above must
 be considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Avalanche accidents of all kinds only happen in avalanche terrain – if avalanche
s are a concern, avoiding avalanche terrain is a sure-fire way to avoid
 avalanche accidents of all kinds, including inter-party accidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choosing 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 to ski (down or up) routes at times that we expect others might be ascending
 or descending is also a form of defensive routefinding.
 Anticipating the choices of others and making our own conservative diversion
 or delay in order to limit the risks we might present to others is a mark
 of a conscientious traveler.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Active measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we ski in start zones, we are potential triggers for avalanches.
 In addition to passive measures to ensure that we are not skiing atop other
 people, there are small measures we can take to communicate with those
 who might be below.
 Radios (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Radios"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) are the superior method of communication in the backcountry, but sup As
 a simple measure, rock climbers and mountaineers yell 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Rope!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 before tossing down a rappel rope, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

On Rappel!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 before rappelling (which can dislodge rock), 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Off Rappel
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to communicate to those above and below, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Rope
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 again, when the rope is pulled (which can generate more rockfall).
 The wording is important, but in the snow world, something akin to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Entering Slope!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Skiing!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Off Slope!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 could provide warning and an opportunity for communication with those below.
 Similarly, for a group entering constrained terrain from below, it might
 be appropriate to shout (or radio (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Radios"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)), 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Entering Couloir!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and make an occasional shout as they ascend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These verbal warnings are, of course, antithetical to a low-impact and quiet
 winter day (and may lead to confusion, as shouts are generally a sign of
 an emergency).
 If the rate of inter-party accidents continues to grow, the necessity of
 such measures, and the approximate skier density at which they are appropriate,
 will become self-evident.
 At a crowded crag, it is perhaps more welcome than it is jarring to hear
 a climber yell, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Rope!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as they begin an orderly descent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to verbal warnings, making micro-route decisions during ascent
 and descent to maximize the leader's ability to see up/down-slope can increase
 the likelihood of noting a potential inter-party conflict before it becomes
 reality.
 
\end_layout

